explanation: The time complexity, denoted as O(n), arises from the loop that calculates the factorial iteratively. In this case, each iteration of the for-loop results in a constant amount of work (multiplication operation). Since n iterations are performed at most when calculating the factorial, it is said to run linearly with respect to the input size \(n\). The space complexity is O(1), which indicates that the memory usage does not increase with an increasing value of \(n\); only a fixed amount of space (to store variables such as `factorial` and loop indices) are required, regardless of how large `n` gets.
